The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	Zurich: World Cup winner Spain topped the latest Fifa rankings, with runner-up Netherlands moving up to second. The reigning world and European champions overtook Brazil, which slipped to third in the table released Wednesday. Meanwhile, India rose one place to 132nd in the latest Fifa rankings. With 160 points in their kitty, India also jumped one place to 21st among 46 nations in the Asian Football Confederation.    
	Rankings    
	1. Spain; 2. The Netherlands; 3. Brazil; 4. Germany; 5. Argentina; 6. Uruguay; 7. England; 8. Portugal; 9. Egypt; 10. Chile        
	Calcutta: Six junior footballers of Siliguri Football Academy have been invited by German club Bayern Munich to train with them. The footballers who have been selected are Nishant Toppo, Sanjib Kerketta, Dipu Burman, Liton Sil, Amit Thakuri and Avishek Chetri.        
	New Delhi: Somdev Dev Varman got off to a winning start at the $75,000 ATP Challenger tournament in Aptos, US, as he beat Japanese Yuichi Sugita 5-7, 6-2, 6-0, in the first round of the hard court event.        
	New Delhi: Hockey India Wednesday set the ball rolling for its much-awaited July 28 elections by releasing names of 56 authorised representatives from 30 state and institutional units to cast their votes.        
	Hyderabad: Hyderabad has been conferred cricket Test centre status by the International Cricket Council and the Board of Control for Cricket in India, making it the ninth city in the country to get the honour. The executive committee was informed about the confirmation of allotment of Test centre status to Hyderabad by the ICC/BCCI, the Hyderabad Cricket Association said in a release Wednesday.        
	Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) has returned the money it had deducted from the funds of Shahid Afridi, Kamran and Umar Akmal and Shoaib Malik, after they were fined heavily earlier this year for indiscipline during the disastrous tour of Australia.         
	Karachi: Shahid Afridi has revealed that he was ready to be the skipper of the national side four-five years ago but the big honour eluded him as the PCB had failed to keep its promise. I was ready (to be the captain) four to five years ago but somebody else was appointed instead, he said.       
